    "On the one hand, a large and highly explosive eruption might be associated with a low level of risk if its occurrence is estimated as very unlikely with a fair degree of confidence.",
    "A moderately explosive but way more likely eruption, on the other hand, would arguably be associated with a higher level of risk.",
    "Despite its simplicity, this way of thinking about risks provides us with an easily applicable and intuitive model for decision-making in contexts of risk that nicely fits with theories of rational choice insisting on the maximisation of the expected utility (see Briggs, 2023).",
